{{Infobox recurring event | name = Narmada Pushkaram | native_name = | native_name_lang = | logo = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | logo_size = 100px | image = File:18-Omkareshwar-0010011-ShreeOmkarMandhata.jpg | image_size = 200px | alt = | caption = [[Omkareshwar]] temple on Narmada river bank | status = Active | genre = [[Hindu festivals]] | begins = | ends = | frequency = every 12 years | venue = | location = [[Narmada River]] | coordinates = | country = [[India]] | first = | founder_name = | last = May 2012 | prev = | next = April 22 - May 5, 2024 | participants = | attendance = | capacity = | area = [[North India]] | budget = | activity = Holy river dip | leader_name = | patron = | organised = <!-- "organized=" also works --> | people = | member = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Narmada Pushkaram''' is a festival of [[Narmada River|River Narmada]] normally occurs once in 12 years. This [[Pushkaram]] is observed for a period of 12 days from the time of entry of [[Jupiter]] into Vrushabha Rasi ([[Taurus (astrology)|Taurus]]).<ref>{{cite book |author=Roshen Dalal |title=Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zrk0AwAAQBAJ&pg=PT921 |date=18 April 2014 |publisher=Penguin Books Limited |isbn=978-81-8475-277-9 |pages=921–}}</ref>
[[Amarkantak | Amarkantak temple]], [[Omkareshwar | Omkareshawar Temple]], [[Chausath_Yogini_Temple,_Jabalpur | Chausath Yogini Temple]], [[Chaubis_Avtar | Chaubis Avatar Temple]], [[Maheshwar Maheshwar Temple]], [[Nemawar]] [[Siddheshwar | Siddheshwar Mandir]] and [[Bhojeshwar Temple|Bhojpur Shiva Temple]] are very ancient and famous. Omkareshawar is one of the twelve [[Jyotirlinga | Jyothirlingas]] and Amrarkantak are the best places to take holy bath in the Naramada river.
