'''USS ''Peacock''''' was a [[sloop-of-war]] in the [[United States Navy]] during the [[War of 1812]].
The ''Peacock'' was authorized by Act of [[United States Congress|Congress]] 3 March 1813, laid down 9 July 1813, by [[Adam and Noah Brown]]<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.1812privateers.org/Privateers/brown.html |title = Noah Brown: shipbuilder War of 1812 |author = |authorlink = |date = 1 March 2008 |work = research sources for the study of privateering during the War of 1812 |publisher = War of 1812: Privateers |accessdate = 25 July 2012 |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/69QNJ8PqU?url=http://www.1812privateers.org/Privateers/brown.html |archivedate = 25 July 2012 |quote = Noah and Adam built the US sloop Peacock at [[Corlear's Hook]], New York, from July through September 1813. |deadurl = yes |df = dmy-all }}</ref> at the [[New York Navy Yard]], and launched 19 September 1813. She served in the War of 1812, capturing twenty ships. Subsequently, she served in the Mediterranean Squadron, and in the "Mosquito Fleet" suppressing Caribbean piracy. She patrolled the South American coast during the colonial wars of independence. She was decommissioned in 1827 and broken up in 1828 to be rebuilt as the '''USS ''Peacock'' (1828)''', intended as an exploration ship. She sailed as part of the [[United States Exploring Expedition]] in 1838. The ''Peacock'' ran aground and broke up on the [[Columbia Bar]] without loss of life in 1841.
==War of 1812== During the [[War of 1812]], the ''Peacock'' made three cruises under the command of [[Master Commandant]] [[Lewis Warrington]]. Departing New York 12 March 1814, she sailed with supplies to the naval station at [[St. Mary's, Georgia]]. Off [[Cape Canaveral, Florida]] 29 April, she captured her an enemy warship, the British [[brig]] {{HMS|Epervier|1812|6}}, which the ''Peacock'' sent to Savannah, and which the United States Navy took into service as the USS ''Epervier''.
{{see also|Capture of HMS Epervier}}
The ''Peacock'' departed Savannah on 4 June on her second cruise; proceeding to the [[Grand Banks]] and along the coasts of Ireland and Spain, she returned via the [[West Indies]] to New York. She captured 14 enemy vessels of various sizes during this journey. On 14 August the ''Peacock'' captured the ''William'', Whiteway, master, of Bristol, and scuttled her.<ref>Farr (1950), p.255.</ref>
The ''Peacock'' departed New York 23 January 1815 with the {{USS|Hornet|1805 brig|2}} and {{USS|Tom Bowline|1814|2}} and rounded the [[Cape of Good Hope]] into the Indian Ocean, where she captured three valuable prizes.
===Last action of the War of 1812=== {{main|Capture of East India Company ship Nautilus}} On 30 June she captured the 16-gun brig ''Nautilus'', which was under the command of Lieutenant Charles Boyce of the [[Bombay Marine]] of the British [[East India Company]] in the [[Straits of Sunda]], in the final naval action of the war. Boyce informed Warrington that the war had ended.<ref name=James/> Warrington suspected a ruse and ordered Boyce to surrender. When Boyce refused, Warrington opened fire, killing one seaman, two European invalids, and three [[lascar]]s, wounding Boyce severely, as well as mortally wounding the first lieutenant, and also wounding five lascars. American casualties amounted to some four or five men wounded.<ref name=James/> When Boyce provided documents proving that the [[Treaty of Ghent]] ending the war had been ratified, Warrington released his victims,<ref>Malcomson (2006), p.363.</ref> though at no point did he in any way inquire about the Boyce's condition or that of any of the injured on the ''Nautilus''.<ref name=James/> The ''Peacock'' returned to New York on 30 October. A court of inquiry in Boston a year later exonerated Warrington of all blame. In his report on the incident, Warrington reported that the British casualties had only been lascars.<ref name=James>James (1837), Vol. 6, pp.266-9.</ref>
==Post-war== The ''Peacock'' left New York on 13 June 1816, bound for France, with the Honorable [[Albert Gallatin]] and party aboard. After pulling into [[Le Havre|Havre de Grâce]] 2 July, she proceeded to join the [[Mediterranean Squadron (United States)|Mediterranean Squadron]]. But for a year of Mediterranean–United States—and return transits, 15 November 1818 – 17 November 1819, the sloop remained with this squadron until 8 May 1821, when she departed for home; she then went into ordinary at the [[Washington Navy Yard]] 10 July.
==Fighting pirates== Pirates were ravaging West Indian shipping in the 1820s and on 3 June 1822, the ''Peacock'' became flagship of Commodore [[David Porter (naval officer)|David Porter]]’s West India Squadron, that rooted out the pirates. The ''Peacock'' served in the expedition that included the [[U.S. Revenue Cutter Service|Revenue Marine]] schooner [[USRC Louisiana (1819)|''Louisiana'']] and the British schooner [[HMS Speedwell (1815)|HMS ''Speedwell'']]. The trio broke up a pirate establishment at [[Bahia Honda Key]] , 28–30 September capturing four vessels. They burnt two and [[prize crew]]s took the other two to New Orleans. Eighteen of the captured pirate crew members were sent to New Orleans for trial.<ref name=King71>King, P 71</ref><ref name=RoM77>Record of Movements, p 77</ref> The ''Peacock'' captured the schooner ''Pilot'' on 10 April 1823 and another sloop 16 April. In September, "malignant fever" necessitated a recess from activities, and the ''Peacock'' pulled into [[Norfolk, Virginia]] on 28 November.
==South Pacific coast and Hawaiʻi== In July 1823, the sloop was involved in the [[Battle of Lake Maracaibo]] and Mr. Peter Storms decided to join the Independentist cause, who won their independence<ref>[http://www.cheguaco.org/rastrojeo.pdf Rastrogeo Margariteño, (spanish) (pdf) (page 40-41)]</ref> on 3 August. Later, in March 1824, the sloop proceeded to the Pacific and for some months cruised along the west coast of South America, where the colonies were struggling for independence. In September 1825, the ''Peacock'' under the command of [[Commodore (rank)|Commodore]] [[Thomas ap Catesby Jones#Between Wars|Thomas ap Catesby Jones]], sailed to the [[Kingdom of Hawaiʻi]], where a treaty of friendship, commerce and navigation was negotiated.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.hawaii-nation.org/treaty1826.html |title= Hawaii-United States Treaty – 1826 |author= Thomas ap Catesby Jones|authorlink=Thomas ap Catesby Jones |author2=[[Kaʻahumanu|Elisabeta Kaahumanu]] |author3=[[Karaimoku]] |author4=[[Boki (Hawaiian chief)|Poki]] |author5=Howapili |author6=Lidia Namahana |date=23 December 1826 |work=Hawaii-nation.org |quote=Entered into force December 23, 1826 |accessdate=26 December 2012 }}</ref><ref>[http://evols.library.manoa.hawaii.edu/bitstream/handle/10524/345/JL17048.pdf?sequence=2 The Hawai'i-United States Treaty of 1826]</ref> From 24 July 1826 until 6 January 1827, the sloop visited other Pacific islands to protect American commerce and the whaling industry. Returning to South America from Hawaii, the ship was struck by a whale, suffering serious damage. Nevertheless, she reached [[Callao]], from which she departed 25 June for New York.<ref name="book">{{cite book |author= Gene A. Smith |title= Thomas ap Catesby Jones, Commodore of Manifest Destiny |publisher= Annapolis, MD: Naval Institute Press |year= 2000 |isbn= 1-55750-848-8 }}</ref>
==USS ''Peacock'' (1828)== [[File:USS Peacock 1813.jpg|200px|right|thumb|''A sketch of the USS Peacock during the [[United States Exploring Expedition|Wilkes Expedition]] in 1838.'']] the ''Peacock'' returned to New York in October 1827 to be decommissioned, broken up and rebuilt in 1828 for a planned expedition of exploration. Her size and configuration stayed about the same, but her guns were reduced to ten: eight long 24-pounders and two long 9-pounders. When plans for the exploratory voyage stalled in Congress, she re-entered regular service in the West Indies from 1829–31. Following refit, both the ''Peacock'' and the newly commissioned ''[[USS Boxer (1832)|Boxer]]'', a 10-gun [[schooner]], were ordered to assist the [[frigate]] [[USS Potomac (1822)|''Potomac'']], which had just sailed on the [[first Sumatran Expedition]]. The two ships were also charged with diplomatic missions. ''Boxer'' left [[Boston Harbor]] about the middle of February 1832, with orders to proceed to [[History of Liberia|Liberia]] and from thence to join the ''Peacock'' off the coast of [[Empire of Brazil|Brazil]]; The ''Peacock'' sailed on 8 March 1832 under [[Commander (United States)|Commander]] [[David Geisinger]].
===Diplomatic missions=== The ''Peacock'' conveyed Mr. [[Francis Baylies]] and family to the [[United Provinces of the River Plate]] (Argentina) to assume the post of United States [[chargé d’affaires]] in the wake of the [[History of the Falkland Islands#USS Lexington raid|USS ''Lexington'' raid on the Falkland Islands]] in 1831. On arrival both the [[HMS Plantagenet (1801)|British line-of-battle ship ''Plantagenet'']] and H. B. M. frigate ''Druid''<ref>[http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~pbtyc/18-1900/D/01478.html Druid, 1825]</ref> complimented her flag by playing ''[[Hail, Columbia]]''.<ref name = "Roberts" />{{rp|pp.25,26}} Also aboard was President [[Andrew Jackson]]'s "special confidential agent" [[Edmund Roberts (diplomat)|Edmund Roberts]] in the official status of [[Captain's clerk#United States Navy|Captain's clerk]].<ref name=Long>{{cite book |last= Long |first= David Foster |authorlink= |title= Gold braid and foreign relations : diplomatic activities of U.S. naval officers, 1798–1883 |url= http://lccn.loc.gov/87034879 |date= 1988 |origyear= |publisher= Naval Institute Press |location= Annapolis |isbn= 9780870212284 |page= 238 |chapter= Chapter Nine |chapterurl= https://books.google.co.th/books?id=yv2sdjw4SIYC&pg=PA209&lpg=PA209&dq=Edmund+Roberts+royal%3B+navy&source=bl&ots=xMsi68ZBY7&sig=_-#v=onepage&q=Edmund%20Roberts%20royal%3B%20navy&f=false|quote=|accessdate= 29 April 2012|laysummary= https://www.jstor.org/stable/2163133 |laydate= February 1990}}</ref>{{rp|p.208}}
25{{nbsp}}June 1832, having left orders for the ''Boxer'' to follow to [[Bengkulu|Bencoolen]], the ''Peacock'' departed [[Montevideo#19th century|war-stricken Montevideo]] for the [[Cape of Good Hope]]. After taking water at [[Tristan da Cunha]] and rounding the Cape, then trying to keep about latitude 38° or 39°, on 9 or 10 August a [[Rogue wave|sea of uncommon height and volume]] struck the ship, and threw her nearly on her beam ends, completely overwhelmed the gig in the starboard-quarter, crushed it into atoms in a moment, and buried the first three [[ratlines]] of the mizen-[[Shroud (sailing)|shroud]]s under water.<ref name = "Roberts" />{{rp|p.31}}
Picking up the southeast [[trade wind]] around ({{coord|16|00|N|102|00|E}},) on 28 August 1832, the ''Peacock'' sailed to Bencoolen where the Dutch [[Resident (title)|Resident]] reported that the ''Potomac'' had completed her mission.<ref name = "Roberts" />{{rp|p.32}} Under orders to gather information before going to [[Cochin-China]], The ''Peacock'' sailed for [[Manila]] by way of Long Island and 'Crokatoa' ([[Krakatoa]]), where [[hot spring]]s found on the eastern side of the islands one hundred and fifty feet from the shore boiled furiously up, through many fathoms of water. Her [[Marine chronometer|chronometer]]s proving useless, the ''Peacock'' threaded the [[Sunda Strait]] by [[Dead reckoning#Marine navigation|dead reckoning]]. [[Diarrhea|Diarrhoea]] and [[dysentery]] prevailed among the crew from [[Anjer|Angier]] to Manila; after a fortnight there, [[Cholera#History|cholera]] struck despite the overall cleanliness of the ship. The ''Peacock'' lost seven crewmen, and many who did recover died later in the voyage of other diseases. No new case of cholera occurred after 2 November 1833 while the ''Peacock'' was under way for [[Macao]]. Within two [[league (unit)#English-speaking world|league]]s of the [[Lamma Island|Lemma]] or [[Wanshan Archipelago|Ladrone islands]], she took aboard a [[Maritime pilot|pilot]] after settling on a fee of thirteen dollars and a bottle of rum.<ref name = "Roberts" />{{rp|p.65}}
After six weeks in the vicinity of [[Guangzhou#17th through 19th centuries|Canton City, China]], with the onset of the winter [[East Asian Monsoon|northeast monsoon]] and no sign of the ''Boxer'', the ''Peacock'' sailed from [[Nei Lingding Island|Lintin Island]] in the [[Pearl River (China)|Pearl River]] estuary for the bay of Turan (modern [[Danang]]) as best for access to [[Hué]], capital of Cochin-China {{ndash}} her task was to explore the possibilities of expanding trade with the kingdom.<ref>{{Cite news |title=China|work=[[The Morning Post]]|date=12 April 1833 |accessdate=13 July 2014 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000174/18330412/015/0003| publisher = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> Contrary winds from the northwest rather than the expected northeast quarter, coupled with a strong southward current, caused her to lose ground on every tack until, on 6 January 1833, she entered what enquiries disclosed to be the Vung-lam harbour of [[Phu Yen province]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vnvietnamtours.com/2011/09/dossier-of-xuan-dai-bay-phu-yen-province-submitted-to-unesco.html|title=Dossier of Xuan Dai Bay (Phu Yen Province) submitted to UNESCO|author=|authorlink=|date=21 September 2011|work=|publisher=Vietnam Tours|accessdate=26 June 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025141731/http://www.vnvietnamtours.com/2011/09/dossier-of-xuan-dai-bay-phu-yen-province-submitted-to-unesco.html|archivedate=25 October 2011|quote=Vung Lam bay used to be the most bustling trading port of Phu Yen in the past, the door connecting Phu Yen to the outer trading worlds.|deadurl=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
On 8 February, Roberts having failed to gain permission to proceed to Hué due to miscommunication, the ''Peacock'' weighed anchor for the [[Gulf of Thailand|gulf of Siam]], where on the 18th she anchored about {{convert|15|mi}} from the [[Samut Prakan Province#Geography|mouth of the river Menam]] at {{coord|13|26|N|100|33|E}}, as was ascertained by frequent [[Lunar distance (navigation)|lunar observations]] and by four chronometers.<ref name = "Roberts" />{{rp|p.229}}
On 20 March 1833 Roberts concluded the [[Siamese-American Treaty of Amity and Commerce]] with the minister representing [[Jessadabodindra|King Rama III]], and the ''Peacock'' departed on 5 April to call on Singapore, where she stayed between 1 and 11 May.
On 29 August in the [[Red Sea]], while bound to [[Mocha, Yemen|Mocha]], the ''Peacock'' encountered the ''Nautilus'', the same brig the ''Peacock'' had attacked after the end of the War of 1812 with Great Britain. The ''Nautilus'' was sailing to [[Surat]] as escort to four brigs crowded with [[Moslem|mussulman]] pilgrims returning from [[Mecca]].<ref name = "Roberts" />{{rp|p.341}} This time the ''Peacock'' did not attack the ''Nautilus''.
Arriving 13 September off [[Muscat, Oman|Muscat]], Roberts concluded a treaty with [[Said bin Sultan, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Sultan Said bin Sultan]], and departed on 7 October 1833. On the voyage from Muscat to [[Mozambique]], Roberts omitted the particulars of each day, but stated that what he had written served "to show the absolute necessity of having first-rate chronometers, or the lunar observations carefully attended to; and never omitted to be taken when practicable."<ref name = "Roberts" />{{rp|p.366}}
The ''Peacock'' returned Roberts to Rio de Janeiro on 17 January 1834, where on 1 March 1834 he boarded the ''Lexington'' to return to Boston.<ref name = "Roberts" />{{rp|p. 400}}<ref name = "Roberts">{{cite book |last= Roberts|first= Edmund |authorlink= Edmund Roberts (diplomat) |title= Embassy to the Eastern courts of Cochin-China, Siam, and Muscat: in the U.S. sloop-of-war Peacock ... during the years 1832-3-4 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=aSgPAAAAYAAJ&oe=UTF-8 |date=12 October 2007 |origyear= First published in 1837 |publisher= Harper & brothers |accessdate= 25 April 2012 }}</ref>
===Return mission=== On 23 April 1835, the ''Peacock'', under the command of [[Cornelius Stribling|C. K. Stribling]], and accompanied by the [[USS Enterprise (1831)|U.S. Schooner ''Enterprise'']], [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commanding]] A. S. Campbell, departed [[New York Harbor]]. Roberts was once again aboard the ''Peacock'', and the two vessels were under the command of Commodore [[Edmund P. Kennedy]]. The mission first sailed to Brazil, then round the [[Cape of Good Hope]] to Zanzibar, for Roberts to return ratifications of the two treaties.
==== Masirah incident ==== On 21 September 1835 at 2&nbsp;am southeast of [[Masirah Island]] about four hundred miles from Muscat, ''Peacock'' grounded on a coral reef in about 2 1/4 [[fathom]]s. Mr. Roberts, and six men under the command of Passed Midshipman William Rogers, left in a small boat to effect a rescue. The crew hove overboard 11 of 22 guns, re-floated the ship on the 23rd, and repelled Arab marauders before making sail the next day. On the 28th the ''Peacock'' was off Muscat when she encountered the sloop-of-war ''Sultan'' under the Muscat flag, and under the command of Mr. Taylor.<ref name = "Rusch"/>{{rp|p.58}}<ref>{{cite journal|author=|last=Richardson|first=Alan|date=December 1979|title=Richardson|journal=Our Illustrious Ancestors|volume=|issue=|pages=|at=Voyage via the Orient: Letters to Home by Charles Richardson|publisher=Katharine's Web|format=|id=|doi=|url=http://katharinesweb.net/Ancestors/Richardson/Richrdson.htm#Anchor-Voyag-4337|accessdate=8 May 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328041922/http://katharinesweb.net/Ancestors/Richardson/Richrdson.htm#Anchor-Voyag-4337|archivedate=28 March 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref group=Note>For a full account of the Masirah incident, see Coupland (1938; pp.370–2).</ref> Said bin Sultan later recovered the guns that had been thrown overboard and shipped them to Roberts free of charge.<ref>{{cite book |last= Gilbert| first= Wesley John |title= Our Man in Zanzibar: Richard Waters, American Consul (1837–1845) | url= http://wesscholar.wesleyan.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1674&context=etd_hon_theses | format= free |accessdate= 3 May 2012 |type= B.A. Thesis |series= Departmental Honors in History |date= April 2011 |publisher= [[Wesleyan University]] |location= Middletown, Connecticut | page= | pages= | nopp = | at= | quote= }})</ref> The ''Peacock'' later obtained this letter:<ref name = "Rusch"/>{{rp|pp.61–62}}<blockquote>I certify that during the period I have navigated the Arabian coast, and been employed in the trigonometrical survey of the same, now executing by order of the Bombay government, that I have ever found it necessary to be careful to take nocturnal as well as diurnal observations, as frequent as possible, owing to the rapidity and fickleness of the currents, which, in some parts, I have found running at the rate of three and four knots an hour, and I have known the ''Palinurus'' set between forty and fifty miles dead in shore, in a dead calm, during the night. It is owing to such currents, that I conceive the United States ship of war ''Peacock'' run aground, as have many British ships in previous years, on and near the same spot; when at the changes of the monsoons, and sometimes at the full and change, you have such thick weather, as to prevent the necessary observations being taken with accuracy and the navigator standing on with confidence as to his position, and with no land in sight, finds himself to his sorrow, often wrong, owing to a deceitful and imperceptible current, which has set him with rapidity upon it. The position of Mazeira Island, is laid down by Owen many miles too much to the westward.
Given under my hand this 10th day of November, 1835.
S. B. Haines. Commander of the Honourable East India Company's surveying brig ''Palinurus.'' To sailing master,
John Weems, U. S. Navy. </blockquote>
A second attempt at negotiation with Cochin-China failed as Roberts fell desperately ill of dysentery; he withdrew to Macao where he died 12 June 1836. [[William Ruschenberger]], [[M.D.]], (1807–1895) [[Medical Corps (United States Navy)|commissioned]] on this voyage,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.artandmedicine.com/biblio/authors/Ruschenberger.html |title= A report on the origin and therapeutic properties of cundurango |author= W.S.W. Ruschenberger, M.D. |authorlink= William Ruschenberger |year= 1873 |work= Published by order of the Navy Department |publisher= [[United States Government Printing Office|G.P.O]] |location= Washington |accessdate= 26 April 2012 |archiveurl= https://www.webcitation.org/67CvMacqX?url=http://www.artandmedicine.com/biblio/authors/Ruschenberger.html |archivedate= 26 April 2012 |quote= Commissioning with the USS Peacock in 1836, William Ruschenberger sailed with Edmund Roberts.... |deadurl= yes |df= dmy-all }}</ref> and gives an account of it up until 27 October 1837 when the ''Peacock'' anchors opposite the city of [[Norfolk, Virginia]], after an absence of more than two years and a half.<ref name = "Rusch">{{cite book |last= Ruschenberger |first= William Samuel Waithman |authorlink= William Ruschenberger|title= A Voyage Round the World: Including an Embassy to Muscat and Siam in 1835, 1836 and 1837. |url= https://archive.org/details/avoyageroundwor00ruscgoog |date=2007-07-24 |origyear= First published in 1837 |publisher= Harper & brothers |location= |oclc= 12492287 |page= |pages= |chapter= |accessdate= 25 April 2012 |edition= |quote= }}</ref>
==Exploration expedition and fate== [[Image:Wreck of the Peacock.jpg|thumb|right|The ''Peacock'' after hitting the bar of the Columbia River.]] The ''Peacock'' joined the [[United States Exploring Expedition]] in 1838, where she did good service before getting stuck on a bar of the [[Columbia River]] in Oregon. She broke up on 17–19 July 1841 after all the crew and much of the scientific data had been taken off, though [[Titian Peale]] lost most of his notes.<ref>Philip K. Lundeberg, "Characteristics of Selected Exploring Vessels," appendix 1 of ''Magnificent Voyagers: The U.S. Exploring Expedition, 1838–1842'', edited by Herman J. Viola and Carolyn Margolis (Smithsonian Institution: 1985), p255.</ref>
